<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="508" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1654,1969]" pageId="13" pageNumber="508">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1726,1752]" pageId="13" pageNumber="508">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Distinct from most other central African species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eaton" authorityYear="1973" box="[909,1051,1726,1752]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Orthotrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[909,1051,1726,1752]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="508">Orthotrichia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the male genitalia more or less symmetrical and having the bilobed processes of the inferior appendages widely divergent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="508" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1654,1969]" pageId="13" pageNumber="508">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1798,1824]" pageId="13" pageNumber="508">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Length of each forewing 
<quantity box="[708,795,1799,1825]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="13" pageNumber="508" unit="mm" value="1.7">1.7 mm</quantity>
(n = 1). Antennae damaged, flagellomeres rectangular in profile. Abdominal segment VII with stout midventral lobe bearing strong setae. Genitalia: segment IX with apical angles produced distally to form processes, each tipped with one seta, dorsally with slender, curved strap terminating in pair of hooks; inferior appendages forming pair of sclerotised pincer-like processes ventrally with stouter pair of conical processes dorsally and bilobed processes slender, elongate and widely divergent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="509" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,150,249]" pageId="14" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,150,176]" pageId="14" pageNumber="509">Etymology.</emphasis>
